# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sparklines
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] Markings and visual elements can be called chartjunk if they are not part of the minimum set of visuals necessary to communicate the information understandably.
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] Another kind of chartjunk skews the depiction and makes it difficult to understand the real data being displayed.
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] Examples of this type include items depicted out of scale to one another, noisy backgrounds making comparison between elements difficult in a chart or graph, and 3-D simulations in line and bar charts.
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] The term *chartjunk* was coined by Edward Tufte in his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information* based on ideas and materials developed for a Princeton statistics course co-taught with John Tukey.
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] The term has been associated with Tufte in other references.
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] In *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information* Tufte claims that good design is founded in minimalist design principles.
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] Specifically, he states that "graphics reveal data" if they are designed with "graphical integrity." Tufte, through minimalist design principles, was committed to an objective and neutral values of science.
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] Other researchers have argued that minimalism is not objective and is full of its own rhetoric and potential to bias.
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] Tufte, in coining the term chartjunk, also made direct comments about a well-known designer at that time, Nigel Holmes.
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] This debate between Tufte and Holmes is emblematic of the tension between statistical and designerly approaches to visualization design.
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] The term chartjunk is an umbrella term that can be used to describe a variety of visual devices and has been referenced by different terms across research.
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] Alternative terms include *embellishment,* *excessive annotation*, decoration, *extraneous elements*, and *unnecessary ornamentation*.
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] Robert Kosara, also a data visualization practitioner, researcher, and author of the blog EagerEyes, noted that not all chartjunk are the same, some are harmful (e.g. a busy background), others harmless (e.g. nice borders or pictures), and some even helpful (e.g. annotations).
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] In a recent study by Parsons and Shukla, they interviewed data visualization designers and found that there is both a "corrective movement" in the design community to move away from minimalist design principles, but also, that designers had different definitions for what constitutes chartjunk.
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] The information visualization research community has researched the effects of chartjunk on how viewers interpret visualizations.
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] There have been studies that found that chartjunk increases long-term memorability of the chart.
[src:sparklines/data-ink-ratio] A recent study found that chartjunk, in the form of semantically meaningful icons, increased accessibility of charts for people with Intellectual and Developmental Disabilities (IDD).
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Edward Rolf Tufte was born in 1942 in Kansas City, Missouri, to Virginia Tufte (1918–2020) and Edward E.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] He grew up in Beverly Hills, California, where his father was a longtime city official.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] He graduated from the public Beverly Hills High School.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Tufte received a BS and a MS in statistics from Stanford University, and a Doctor of Philosophy in political science from Yale University.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] His dissertation was completed in 1968 and titled *The Civil Rights Movement and Its Opposition*.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Tufte was hired in 1967 by the Woodrow Wilson School of Princeton University as a lecturer in politics and public affairs, where he steadily moved up to the rank of full Professor in 1972.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] He taught courses there in political economy and data analysis while publishing three quantitatively inclined political science books.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] In 1975, while at Princeton, Tufte was asked to teach a statistics course to a group of journalists who were visiting the school to study economics.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] He developed a set of readings and lectures on statistical graphics, which he further developed in joint seminars he taught with renowned statistician John Tukey, a pioneer in the field of information design.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] These course materials became the foundation for Tufte's first book on information design, *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] In 1977, Tufte left Princeton University for Yale University, where he accepted an appointment as Professor of Political Science, Statistics, and Computer Science, as well as a Senior Critic at the Yale School of Art.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] After negotiations with major publishers failed, Tufte decided to self-publish the book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information* in 1982, working closely with graphic designer Howard Gralla.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Tufte financed the work by taking out a second mortgage on his home.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] The book quickly became a commercial success and secured Tufte's transition from political scientist to information expert.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] In 1999, after 22 years of service at Yale University, his professorship at Yale was made Emeritus.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] On March 5, 2010, President Barack Obama appointed Tufte to the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act's Recovery Independent Advisory Panel "to provide transparency in the use of Recovery-related funds".
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Tufte is an expert in the presentation of infographics such as charts and diagrams, and is a fellow of the American Statistical Association.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] He has held fellowships from the Guggenheim Foundation and the Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Tufte's writing is important in such fields as information design and visual literacy, which deal with the visual communication of information.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] He coined the word *chartjunk* to refer to useless, non-informative, or information-obscuring elements of quantitative information displays.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Tufte's other key concepts include what he calls the *lie factor*, the *data-ink ratio*, and the *data density* of a graphic.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Tufte uses the term "data-ink ratio" to argue against using excessive decoration in visual displays of quantitative information.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] In *Visual Display*, Tufte explains, "Sometimes decoration can help editorialize about the substance of the graphic.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Tufte encourages the use of data-rich illustrations that present all available data.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] When such illustrations are examined closely, every data point has a value, but when they are looked at more generally, only trends and patterns can be observed.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Tufte suggests these macro/micro readings be presented in the space of an eye-span, in the high resolution format of the printed page, and at the unhurried pace of the viewer's leisure.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Tufte uses several historical examples to make his case.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] These include John Snow's cholera outbreak map, Charles Joseph Minard's *Carte Figurative*, early space debris plots, Galileo Galilei's *Sidereus Nuncius*, and Maya Lin's Vietnam Veterans Memorial.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] For instance, the listing of the names of deceased soldiers on the black granite of Lin's sculptural memorial is shown to be more powerful as a chronological list rather than as an alphabetical one.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] The sacrifice each fallen individual has made is thus highlighted within the overall time scope of the war.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] In *Sidereus Nuncius*, Galileo presents the nightly observations of the moons of Jupiter in relation to the body itself, interwoven with the two-month narrative record.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Tufte has criticized the way Microsoft PowerPoint is typically used.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Tufte cites the way PowerPoint was used by NASA engineers in the events leading to the Space Shuttle Columbia disaster as an example of PowerPoint's many problems.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] The software style is designed to persuade rather than to inform people of technical details.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Instead, Tufte argues that the most effective way of presenting information in a technical setting, such as an academic seminar or a meeting of industry experts, is by distributing a brief written report that can be read by all participants in the first 5 to 10 minutes of the meeting.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Tufte believes that this is the most efficient method of transferring knowledge from the presenter to the audience and then the rest of the meeting is devoted to discussion and debate.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] One method Tufte encourages to allow quick visual comparison of multiple series is the small multiple, a chart with many series shown on a single pair of axes that can often be easier to read when displayed as several separate pairs of axes placed next to each other.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] He suggests this is particularly helpful when the series are measured on quite different vertical (*y*-axis) scales, but over the same range on the horizontal *x*-axis (usually time).
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] These are often used as elements of a small multiple with several lines used together.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Tufte explains the sparkline as a kind of "word" that conveys rich information without breaking the flow of a sentence or paragraph made of other "words" both visual and conventional.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] To date, the earliest known implementation of sparklines was conceived by interaction designer Peter Zelchenko and implemented by programmer Mike Medved in early 1998.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Beyond his academic endeavors over the years, Tufte has created sculptures, often large outdoor ones made of metal or stone, that were first primarily exhibited on his own rural Connecticut property.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] In 2009–10, some of these artworks were exhibited at the Aldrich Contemporary Art Museum in Ridgefield, Connecticut, in the one-man show *Edward Tufte: Seeing Around*.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] Hogpen Hill Farms, the 234-acre (95-hectare) Tufte sculpture garden in Woodbury, Connecticut, is open to the public on summer weekends.
[src:sparklines/edward-tufte] In 2010, Edward Tufte opened a gallery, ET Modern, in New York City's Chelsea Art District at 11th Avenue and 20th Street.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] A **line chart** or **line graph**, also known as **curve chart**, is a type of chart that displays information as a series of data points called 'markers' connected by straight line segments.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] It is a basic type of chart common in many fields.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] It is similar to a scatter plot except that the measurement points are ordered (typically by their x-axis value) and joined with straight line segments.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] A line chart is often used to visualize a trend in data over intervals of time – a time series – thus the line is often drawn chronologically.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] In these cases they are known as run charts.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] Some of the earliest known line charts are generally credited to Francis Hauksbee, Nicolaus Samuel Cruquius, Johann Heinrich Lambert and the Scottish engineer William Playfair.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] Line charts often display time as a variable on the x-axis.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] Playfair was one of the first to visualize data this way.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] In 1786, he plotted ten years of money spent by the Royal Navy.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] He supplemented the chart with a detailed description, telling his readers how to interpret the change over time because they were unfamiliar with this form of abstract visualization.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] In addition to line charts, Playfair invented and popularized bar charts and pie charts.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] In the experimental sciences, data collected from experiments are often visualized by a graph.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] Such a table representation of data is a great way to display exact values, but it can prevent the discovery and understanding of patterns in the values.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] In addition, a table display is often erroneously considered to be an objective, neutral collection or storage of the data (and may in that sense even be erroneously considered to be the data itself) whereas it is in fact just one of various possible visualizations of the data.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] Understanding the process described by the data in the table is aided by producing a graph or line chart of *speed versus time*.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] Such a visualisation appears in the figure to the right.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] This visualization can let the viewer quickly understand the entire process at a glance.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] This visualization can however be misunderstood, especially when expressed as showing the mathematical function $v(t)$ that expresses the speed v (the dependent variable) as a function of time t .
[src:sparklines/line-chart] This can be misunderstood as showing speed to be a variable that is dependent only on time.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] This would however only be true in the case of an object being acted on only by a constant force acting in a vacuum.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] Charts often include an overlaid mathematical function depicting the best-fit trend of the scattered data.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] This layer is referred to as a best-fit layer and the graph containing this layer is often referred to as a line graph.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] It is highly unlikely that the experimental error in the data is negligible, yet the curve falls exactly through each of the data points.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] In either case, the best-fit layer can reveal trends in the data.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] Further, measurements such as the gradient or the area under the curve can be made visually, leading to more conclusions or results from the data table.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] A true best-fit layer should depict a continuous mathematical function whose parameters are determined by using a suitable error-minimization scheme, which appropriately weights the error in the data values.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] Such curve fitting functionality is often found in graphing software or spreadsheets.
[src:sparklines/line-chart] Best-fit curves may vary from simple linear equations to more complex quadratic, polynomial, exponential, and periodic curves.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] A **small multiple** (sometimes called **trellis chart**, **lattice chart**, **grid chart**, or **panel chart**) is a series of similar graphs or charts using the same scale and axes, allowing them to be easily compared.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] It uses multiple views to show different partitions of a dataset.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] The term was popularized by Edward Tufte.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] In the example, the departmental salary expense is charted by month with a dashed line indicating the average for each department.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] The scales on each panel are different to emphasize the relative change over time compared to the range.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] Standardizing the scales could provide insight into comparisons in magnitude between the different departments.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] Two independent Y axes may be utilized when presenting data with different numeric scales in each panel.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] Muybridge's work not only proved for the first time that all four of a horse's hooves left the ground during gallop (see upper central plates), but it also broke new ground in terms of artistic expression and became foundational to the development of the motion picture.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] Muybridge went on to produce many more examples of small multiples showing animal locomotion through the medium of stop-motion photography, including boys playing leapfrog and a bison cantering.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] Adjacent is a chart showing the population broken down by occupation, including a count of those attending school, according to the 1870 Census.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] This graphic is innovative in its use of both a treemap display and a latticed layout of small multiples.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] Additional examples appearing in the *Atlas* include side-by-side geographic maps showing the changes in population over time, as well as tiled mosaic charts showing population demographic breakdowns, and diverging bar graphs showing deaths broken down by age and gender, tiled by state.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] Small multiples are a popular technique in cartographic design for multivariate mapping.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] As with the small multiple chart, each panel uses the same underlying two-dimensional space, but in this case that is a geographic space.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] Typically, the variables being mapped are of a similar type, such as types of agricultural products, so that the same strategy of map symbol can be used on each panel, enabling rapid comparison between the maps.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] Another common use of small multiples is to show change in spatial patterns over time, as an alternative to an animated map.
[src:sparklines/small-multiple] Several tests of the effectiveness of each method have generally concluded that they have distinct advantages, with animation being better for seeing trends, especially movement, and small multiples being better for making comparisons between times.
[src:sparklines/sparkline] A **sparkline** is a very small line chart, typically drawn without axes or coordinates.
[src:sparklines/sparkline] It presents the general shape of a variation (typically over time) in some measurement, such as temperature or stock market price, in a simple and highly condensed way.
[src:sparklines/sparkline] Whereas a typical chart is designed to professionally show as much data as possible, and is set off from the flow of text, sparklines are intended to be succinct, memorable, and located where they are discussed.
[src:sparklines/sparkline] Sparklines are small enough to be embedded in text, or several sparklines may be grouped together as elements of a small multiple.
[src:sparklines/sparkline] In 1762 Laurence Sterne used typographical devices in his sixth volume of The Life and Opinions of Tristram Shandy, Gentleman to illustrate his narrative proceeding: "These were the four lines I moved through my first, second, third, and fourth volumes,–".
[src:sparklines/sparkline] The 1888 monograph describing the 1883 eruption of Krakatoa shows barometric signatures of the event obtained at various stations around the world in the same fashion, but in separate plates (VII & VIII), not within the text.
[src:sparklines/sparkline] Edward Tufte documented a compact style in 1983 called "intense continuous time-series".
[src:sparklines/sparkline] He introduced the term *sparkline* in 2006 for "small, high resolution graphics embedded in a context of words, numbers, images", which are "data-intense, design-simple, word-sized graphics".
[src:sparklines/sparkline] Later in 2020, Tufte attributed the idea to Donald Knuth's "METAFONTbook".
[src:sparklines/sparkline] The first software sparkline was programmed in 1999 by Peter Zelchenko.
[src:sparklines/sparkline] He introduced "an inline-chart" feature for Mike Medved's QuoteTracker.
[src:sparklines/sparkline] TD Ameritrade later discontinued QuoteTracker.
[src:sparklines/sparkline] On May 7, 2008, Microsoft employees filed a patent application for the implementation of sparklines in Microsoft Excel 2010.
[src:sparklines/sparkline] The application was published on November 12, 2009, prompting Tufte to express concerns about patent breadth and non-novelty.
[src:sparklines/sparkline] On 23 January, 2009, MultiRacio Ltd. published an OpenOffice.org Calc extension named "EuroOffice Sparkline".
[src:sparklines/sparkline] On March 3, 2022, Tomaž Vajngerl implemented sparklines in LibreOffice Calc version 7.4, including support for importing sparklines from the OOXML Workbook format.
[src:sparklines/sparkline] Sparklines are frequently used in line with text.
[src:sparklines/sparkline] The sparkline should be about the same height as the text around it.
[src:sparklines/sparkline] Tufte offers some useful design principles for the sizing of sparklines to maximize their readability.
[src:sparklines/time-series] In mathematics, a **time series** is a sequence of data points indexed, listed, or graphed in chronological order.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Most commonly, a time series consists of observations recorded at successive equally spaced points in time.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Thus, it represents a form of discrete-time data.
[src:sparklines/time-series] A time series may describe measurements collected over seconds, days, years, or even centuries.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Common examples include heights of ocean tides, counts of sunspots, daily temperature readings, and the closing values of stock market indices such as the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:sparklines/time-series] A time series is often visualized using a run chart (a type of temporal line chart), which helps identify patterns such as trends, seasonal effects, and irregular fluctuations.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Time series data have a natural temporal ordering.
[src:sparklines/time-series] This makes time series analysis distinct from cross-sectional studies, in which there is no natural ordering of the observations (e.g. explaining people's wages by reference to their respective education levels, where the individuals' data could be entered in any order).
[src:sparklines/time-series] Time series analysis is also distinct from spatial data analysis where the observations typically relate to geographical locations (e.g. accounting for house prices by the location as well as the intrinsic characteristics of the houses).
[src:sparklines/time-series] A stochastic model for a time series will generally reflect the fact that observations close together in time will be more closely related than observations further apart.
[src:sparklines/time-series] In addition, time series models will often make use of the natural one-way ordering of time so that values for a given period will be expressed as deriving in some way from past values, rather than from future values (see time reversibility).
[src:sparklines/time-series] Time series analysis can be applied to real-valued, continuous data, discrete numeric data, or discrete symbolic data (i.e. sequences of characters, such as letters and words in the English language).
[src:sparklines/time-series] Methods for time series analysis may be divided into two classes: frequency-domain methods and time-domain methods.
[src:sparklines/time-series] The former include spectral analysis and wavelet analysis; the latter include auto-correlation and cross-correlation analysis.
[src:sparklines/time-series] In the time domain, correlation and analysis can be made in a filter-like manner using scaled correlation, thereby mitigating the need to operate in the frequency domain.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Additionally, time series analysis techniques may be divided into parametric and non-parametric methods.
[src:sparklines/time-series] The parametric approaches assume that the underlying stationary stochastic process has a certain structure which can be described using a small number of parameters (for example, using an autoregressive or moving-average model).
[src:sparklines/time-series] In these approaches, the task is to estimate the parameters of the model that describes the stochastic process.
[src:sparklines/time-series] By contrast, non-parametric approaches explicitly estimate the covariance or the spectrum of the process without assuming that the process has any particular structure.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Methods of time series analysis may also be divided into linear and non-linear, and univariate and multivariate.
[src:sparklines/time-series] A time series is one type of panel data.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Panel data is the general class, a multidimensional data set, whereas a time series data set is a one-dimensional panel (as is a cross-sectional dataset).
[src:sparklines/time-series] A data set may exhibit characteristics of both panel data and time series data.
[src:sparklines/time-series] One way to tell is to ask what makes one data record unique from the other records.
[src:sparklines/time-series] If the answer is the time data field, then this is a time series data set candidate.
[src:sparklines/time-series] If determining a unique record requires a time data field and an additional identifier which is unrelated to time (e.g. student ID, stock symbol, country code), then it is panel data candidate.
[src:sparklines/time-series] If the differentiation lies on the non-time identifier, then the data set is a cross-sectional data set candidate.
[src:sparklines/time-series] There are several types of motivation and data analysis available for time series which are appropriate for different purposes.
[src:sparklines/time-series] In the context of statistics, econometrics, quantitative finance, seismology, meteorology, and geophysics the primary goal of time series analysis is forecasting.
[src:sparklines/time-series] In the context of signal processing, control engineering and communication engineering it is used for signal detection.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Other applications are in data mining, pattern recognition and machine learning, where time series analysis can be used for clustering, classification, query by content, anomaly detection as well as forecasting.
[src:sparklines/time-series] A simple way to examine a regular time series is manually with a line chart.
[src:sparklines/time-series] The datagraphic shows tuberculosis deaths in the United States, along with the yearly change and the percentage change from year to year.
[src:sparklines/time-series] The total number of deaths declined in every year until the mid-1980s, after which there were occasional increases, often proportionately - but not absolutely - quite large.
[src:sparklines/time-series] A study of corporate data analysts found two challenges to exploratory time series analysis: discovering the shape of interesting patterns, and finding an explanation for these patterns.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Visual tools that represent time series data as heat map matrices can help overcome these challenges.
[src:sparklines/time-series] This approach may be based on harmonic analysis and filtering of signals in the frequency domain using the Fourier transform, and spectral density estimation.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Its development was significantly accelerated during World War II by mathematician Norbert Wiener, electrical engineers Rudolf E.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Kálmán, Dennis Gabor and others for filtering signals from noise and predicting signal values at a certain point in time.
[src:sparklines/time-series] An equivalent effect may be achieved in the time domain, as in a Kalman filter; see filtering and smoothing for more techniques.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Curve fitting is the process of constructing a curve, or mathematical function, that has the best fit to a series of data points, possibly subject to constraints.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Curve fitting can involve either interpolation, where an exact fit to the data is required, or smoothing, in which a "smooth" function is constructed that approximately fits the data.
[src:sparklines/time-series] A related topic is regression analysis, which focuses more on questions of statistical inference such as how much uncertainty is present in a curve that is fit to data observed with random errors.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Fitted curves can be used as an aid for data visualization, to infer values of a function where no data are available, and to summarize the relationships among two or more variables.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Extrapolation refers to the use of a fitted curve beyond the range of the observed data, and is subject to a degree of uncertainty since it may reflect the method used to construct the curve as much as it reflects the observed data.
[src:sparklines/time-series] For processes that are expected to generally grow in magnitude one of the curves in the graphic (and many others) can be fitted by estimating their parameters.
[src:sparklines/time-series] The construction of economic time series involves the estimation of some components for some dates by interpolation between values ("benchmarks") for earlier and later dates.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Interpolation is estimation of an unknown quantity between two known quantities (historical data), or drawing conclusions about missing information from the available information ("reading between the lines").
[src:sparklines/time-series] Interpolation is useful where the data surrounding the missing data is available and its trend, seasonality, and longer-term cycles are known.
[src:sparklines/time-series] This is often done by using a related series known for all relevant dates.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Alternatively polynomial interpolation or spline interpolation is used where piecewise polynomial functions are fitted in time intervals such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:sparklines/time-series] A different problem which is closely related to interpolation is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function (also called regression).
[src:sparklines/time-series] The main difference between regression and interpolation is that polynomial regression gives a single polynomial that models the entire data set.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Spline interpolation, however, yield a piecewise continuous function composed of many polynomials to model the data set.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Extrapolation is the process of estimating, beyond the original observation range, the value of a variable on the basis of its relationship with another variable.
[src:sparklines/time-series] It is similar to interpolation, which produces estimates between known observations, but extrapolation is subject to greater uncertainty and a higher risk of producing meaningless results.
[src:sparklines/time-series] In general, a function approximation problem asks us to select a function among a well-defined class that closely matches ("approximates") a target function in a task-specific way.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Second, the target function, call it *g*, may be unknown; instead of an explicit formula, only a set of points (a time series) of the form (*x*, *g*(*x*)) is provided.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Depending on the structure of the domain and codomain of *g*, several techniques for approximating *g* may be applicable.
[src:sparklines/time-series] For example, if *g* is an operation on the real numbers, techniques of interpolation, extrapolation, regression analysis, and curve fitting can be used.
[src:sparklines/time-series] If the codomain (range or target set) of *g* is a finite set, one is dealing with a classification problem instead.
[src:sparklines/time-series] A related problem of *online* time series approximation is to summarize the data in one-pass and construct an approximate representation that can support a variety of time series queries with bounds on worst-case error.
[src:sparklines/time-series] To some extent, the different problems (regression, classification, fitness approximation) have received a unified treatment in statistical learning theory, where they are viewed as supervised learning problems.
[src:sparklines/time-series] In statistics, prediction is a part of statistical inference.
[src:sparklines/time-series] One particular approach to such inference is known as predictive inference, but the prediction can be undertaken within any of the several approaches to statistical inference.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Indeed, one description of statistics is that it provides a means of transferring knowledge about a sample of a population to the whole population, and to other related populations, which is not necessarily the same as prediction over time.
[src:sparklines/time-series] When information is transferred across time, often to specific points in time, the process is known as forecasting.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Assigning time series pattern to a specific category, for example identify a word based on series of hand movements in sign language.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Splitting a time-series into a sequence of segments.
[src:sparklines/time-series] It is often the case that a time-series can be represented as a sequence of individual segments, each with its own characteristic properties.
[src:sparklines/time-series] For example, the audio signal from a conference call can be partitioned into pieces corresponding to the times during which each person was speaking.
[src:sparklines/time-series] In time-series segmentation, the goal is to identify the segment boundary points in the time-series, and to characterize the dynamical properties associated with each segment.
[src:sparklines/time-series] One can approach this problem using change-point detection, or by modeling the time-series as a more sophisticated system, such as a Markov jump linear system.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Time series data may be clustered, however special care has to be taken when considering subsequence clustering.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Subsequence time series clustering resulted in unstable (random) clusters *induced by the feature extraction* using chunking with sliding windows.
[src:sparklines/time-series] It was found that the cluster centers (the average of the time series in a cluster - also a time series) follow an arbitrarily shifted sine pattern (regardless of the dataset, even on realizations of a random walk).
[src:sparklines/time-series] This means that the found cluster centers are non-descriptive for the dataset because the cluster centers are always nonrepresentative sine waves.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Models for time series data can have many forms and represent different stochastic processes.
[src:sparklines/time-series] When modeling variations in the level of a process, three broad classes of practical importance are the *autoregressive* (AR) models, the *integrated* (I) models, and the *moving-average* (MA) models.
[src:sparklines/time-series] These three classes depend *linearly* on previous data points.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Combinations of these ideas produce autoregressive moving-average (ARMA) and autoregressive integrated moving-average (ARIMA) models.
[src:sparklines/time-series] The autoregressive fractionally integrated moving-average (ARFIMA) model generalizes the former three.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Another important generalization is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, in which the AR coefficients are allowed to change over time, enabling the model to capture evolving or non-stationary dynamics.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Extensions of these classes to deal with vector-valued data are available under the heading of multivariate time-series models and sometimes the preceding acronyms are extended by including an initial "V" for "vector", as in VAR for vector autoregression.
[src:sparklines/time-series] For these models, the acronyms are extended with a final "X" for "exogenous".
[src:sparklines/time-series] Time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) models are especially useful for analyzing non-stationary time series in which the underlying dynamics evolve over time in complex ways, not limited to classical forms of variation such as trends or seasonal patterns.
[src:sparklines/time-series] This flexibility makes them well suited to modeling structural changes, regime shifts, or gradual evolutions in a system's behavior.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Estimation of TVAR models typically involves methods such as kernel smoothing, recursive least squares, or Kalman filtering.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Non-linear dependence of the level of a series on previous data points is of interest, partly because of the possibility of producing a chaotic time series.
[src:sparklines/time-series] However, more importantly, empirical investigations can indicate the advantage of using predictions derived from non-linear models, over those from linear models, as for example in nonlinear autoregressive exogenous models.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Among other types of non-linear time series models, there are models to represent the changes of variance over time (heteroskedasticity).
[src:sparklines/time-series] These models represent autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) and the collection comprises a wide variety of representation (GARCH, TARCH, EGARCH, FIGARCH, CGARCH, etc.).
[src:sparklines/time-series] Here changes in variability are related to, or predicted by, recent past values of the observed series.
[src:sparklines/time-series] This is in contrast to other possible representations of locally varying variability, where the variability might be modeled as being driven by a separate time-varying process, as in a doubly stochastic model.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Multiscale (often referred to as multiresolution) techniques decompose a given time series, attempting to illustrate time dependence at multiple scales.
[src:sparklines/time-series] See also Markov switching multifractal (MSMF) techniques for modeling volatility evolution.
[src:sparklines/time-series] A hidden Markov model (HMM) is a statistical Markov model in which the system being modeled is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.
[src:sparklines/time-series] An HMM can be considered as the simplest dynamic Bayesian network.
[src:sparklines/time-series] HMM models are widely used in speech recognition, for translating a time series of spoken words into text.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Many of these models are collected in the python package sktime.
[src:sparklines/time-series] A number of different notations are in use for time-series analysis.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Ergodicity implies stationarity, but the converse is not necessarily the case.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Stationarity is usually classified into strict stationarity and wide-sense or second-order stationarity.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Both models and applications can be developed under each of these conditions, although the models in the latter case might be considered as only partly specified.
[src:sparklines/time-series] In addition, time-series analysis can be applied where the series are seasonally stationary or non-stationary.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Situations where the amplitudes of frequency components change with time can be dealt with in time-frequency analysis which makes use of a time–frequency representation of a time-series or signal.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Time series can be visualized with two categories of chart: Overlapping Charts and Separated Charts.
[src:sparklines/time-series] Jevons was the first to study times series.
[src:sparklines/time-series] In his book he examined a number of weekly financial time series between the years 1825 to 1860 inclusive.
[src:sparklines/time-series] These included times series of bankruptcies, currency circulation and discount rates.
